1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
 Baby. Okay, let's quickly pray, guys. Okay, this is Jennifer.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:11,000
 Jennifer looks after our community groups and does a lot of wonderful work connecting with people,

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:14,000
 helping people stay connected with each other in our church.

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
 So if you would stretch out your hand, let's pray for Jennifer.

5
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:22,000
 Jesus, we thank you for Jennifer. We thank you for this baby's cries, Lord.

6
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 And we just ask that you would speak through Jennifer, Lord, this message that you've given to her.

7
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,000
 There's something for everybody to take from it this afternoon, Lord.

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 So I just pray that you would use her according to your purpose this afternoon.

9
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,000
 In Jesus' name we pray. Amen.

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,000
 Thank you, Alison.

11
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:46,000
 Good afternoon, church.

12
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:48,000
 Yeah, good to see you all.

13
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 And it's great to share a message, share from the Bible with you all this afternoon.

14
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:02,000
 So as Alison said, last week, Pastor Andrew opened a new sermon series on public faith.

15
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:05,000
 So he asked us a question last week, I think it's good to recap,

16
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 that what should a Christian do when the whole world has gone crazy?

17
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:15,000
 I'm wrestling with this question as well, and I hope you do as well.

18
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 So starting, so he emphasized that we are all called to be sought and liked,

19
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 to demonstrate, to live out our faith and the love of Jesus to the people around us.

20
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:34,000
 And today we will look into one aspect of our life, which is very important, which is our work.

21
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 So the coming weeks we will be looking into different aspects.

22
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,000
 But today we will look into our workplace.

23
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:49,000
 And I think most of us here spend the most hours of the week at our work, right?

24
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:54,000
 So this is really a very important area for us to think through,

25
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 how we live our faith publicly to the people around us.

26
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 And if you remember, two weeks ago, Pastor John also preached on a message about workplace.

27
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:12,000
 And he emphasized that there is no such separation between secular and sacred.

28
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 And in fact, we are all called to evangelize in the workplace.

29
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:22,000
 And he gave us some great tips on how to evangelize as well.

30
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 So if you miss any of the two weeks, we encourage you to catch up on YouTube.

31
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:36,000
 And today we will look into living our faith publicly in the workplace from a different perspective.

32
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
 So if you, let's say if we all go to work eight hours per day,

33
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:47,000
 we can't be spending eight hours to evangelize, right?

34
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:52,000
 If you do, then I'll be worried, unless you're a missionary.

35
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:58,000
 So there must be some purpose when we are doing our actual work, right?

36
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:05,000
 Otherwise, it will be just very frustrating if there's no purpose at all when we do our actual work.

37
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:12,000
 So last week, Pastor Andrew reminded us that living our faith can look differently.

38
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:25,000
 It can be revealed by how we live, by our lifestyles, by our beliefs, by our choices, by our habits, our character, how we use our resources.

39
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 So it's the same to the workplace.

40
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:35,000
 We can reveal our faith to other people by how we work as well.

41
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:39,000
 So let us open with a few questions that we ask ourselves.

42
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 How do we make our faith public when we are doing our daily work?

43
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 How do we demonstrate our values as Christians when we are actually working?

44
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:02,000
 And how do we live as salt and light in the workplace, being a blessing to those we work alongside?

45
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:12,000
 And before we answer these questions, perhaps we need to take a step back on how we think about our work.

46
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 Over these years, I've heard a lot of Christians struggle to see God when we work, and also to see the purposes in our work.

47
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:28,000
 And if I'm honest, I struggled with that at some point as well.

48
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 So before I joined the staff team at the Vine, I was actually a paralegal.

49
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 So I worked in the legal industry for a few years.

50
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 And as you can imagine, as a legal professional, we can be super occupied.

51
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 And I felt like I didn't really have time to think about God when I work.

52
00:04:50,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 Every day I go into my office, then I'm occupied by tons of emails and phone calls from my bosses, from my clients,

53
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 from all the different things that we are handling with.

54
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:08,000
 And I really struggle to see God.

55
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 I felt like I heard a lot of voices from different people, but God's voice.

56
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 I really struggle with that.

57
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:25,000
 And how I cope with it, I don't recommend that, but I will share how I cope with that.

58
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,000
 So I just fill my free time with a lot of Christian activities.

59
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:36,000
 Of course, Sunday services, I go to my CGs, I sign up for different Bible studies, and I serve at church as well.

60
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 I just fill my schedule up, and that makes me feel like, oh, each day I have something that I'm doing in the church.

61
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:47,000
 So each day I have some moments I'm connected with God.

62
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 So, again, do not recommend this. It's not sustainable.

63
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 You only have that much energy when you were in early 20s.

64
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:59,000
 So not anymore for me now.

65
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:07,000
 And so if I'm honest with you, to a little bit further reflection on how we passed that into share last week,

66
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 I was actually escaping the reality that I struggle in the workplace.

67
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 And I'm sure I'm not alone in this room.

68
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
 We might cope with that differently.

69
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 There are four models that were mentioned by Pastor Andrew to escape, like me, to insulate, to control, or to conform.

70
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 So I'm not sure what your reflection is like, but at some point we are like that.

71
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:42,000
 Come on Sunday, we worship with our brothers and sisters, feeling super recharged spiritually.

72
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 But the next day, when we go back to the office, facing the reality that our workplace is full of brokenness,

73
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:57,000
 full of sinfulness, full of unfairness, that we struggle to see God again.

74
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:06,000
 So, is it really like this when we work?

75
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 Are there any other values apart from earning our daily bread in our work?

76
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 So let's pause a moment to ask ourselves a question.

77
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 What motivates us to go to work each day?

78
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 And what motivates us to do our work each day?

79
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:36,000
 Paul in Colossians actually talks about how we could approach our work.

80
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:43,000
 He says in Colossians 3 that Jesus is risen and we are all raised with Jesus.

81
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:51,000
 And he calls us as Christians to put our sinful nature to death and to live for Jesus Christ.

82
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:57,000
 And then he talks about different types of relationships and how Christians should live those relationships.

83
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 And then he talks about the relationships between slaves and masters.

84
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
 And then he says this.

85
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:32,000
 Here Paul is shifting our perspective on how we should approach work and work relationship as Christians.

86
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
 He calls us to see all that we are doing as a serving to Jesus.

87
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 And we are to do everything with all our hearts for his sake.

88
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 But there's one thing that I want to clarify.

89
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 That's something Paul is not talking about.

90
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 So Paul is not calling us to tolerate slavery and injustice in our workplace.

91
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 We don't brainwash ourselves by saying, "Oh, I'm working for Jesus. I'm doing that for Jesus."

92
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
 And then we just continue to suffer in our workplace.

93
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:12,000
 This is not something Paul is talking about.

94
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:21,000
 Instead, Paul is reminding us that Jesus is sovereign in every aspect of our lives.

95
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 And he is bringing transformation to the world.

96
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 So he is inviting us as Christians to be part of his work.

97
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:39,000
 So we work with him and we bring transformation to the world with God.

98
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:46,000
 So as we are working, our motivation shouldn't come from the world or come from our bosses.

99
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 But at the same time, he's not calling us to disregard everything about our human bosses either.

100
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 But he's calling us to do this.

101
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:01,000
 As we are rendering what is right and what is wrong,

102
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:08,000
 we should be considering what is fitting in the Lord as our priority.

103
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,000
 So we need to think about this.

104
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 Are we demonstrating the sovereignty of Jesus as we work?

105
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:22,000
 Are we working as in we are working for Jesus?

106
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:28,000
 Is there a way for us Christians to work that can reflect Jesus as our Lord?

107
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:31,000
 That is visible to other people?

108
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:39,000
 And what does it look like to be sought and liked in our workplaces through the way we work

109
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:43,000
 that reflect Jesus' heart and character?

110
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:47,000
 So on this, we can talk about many different topics.

111
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:52,000
 In fact, in the Bible, Jesus has demonstrated his character.

112
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:55,000
 And there are so many of them that we can apply to our workplace.

113
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:05,000
 We can talk about topics like humility or generosity, patience, kindness, or even forgiveness.

114
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:10,000
 But there's one that I feel is really important for us as Christians

115
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 for becoming the sought and liked to the world

116
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:20,000
 and to approach our workplaces in a right mindset and values.

117
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:27,000
 And I would like to call that as a Christ-centered integrity.

118
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:33,000
 So when we hear about the word integrity, I don't know what comes to your mind.

119
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:38,000
 So in English, it means honesty and uprightness.

120
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 We use this word to describe someone who demonstrates a very strong ethic, perhaps.

121
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
 So any musical fans here?

122
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:51,000
 Yay! Yay!

123
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:57,000
 So if you know the story of Les Miserables, there's a character called Chaffer.

124
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 He is an inspector. He sees that everyone follows the law to serve Jesus Christ.

125
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 And he almost takes it in a very legalistic way.

126
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:18,000
 He's quite uncompassionate, and there's no grace in that area, which is quite sad.

127
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 And this is not the character of God either.

128
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 I can go on talking about limits, but let's focus on this.

129
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:34,000
 But the Bible, the word integrity in the Bible has such a rich meaning that I want to share with you today.

130
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 So we will look into the Old Testament usage of the word integrity.

131
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:47,000
 And the first usage, which is more common, which is zedek, which means righteousness.

132
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:55,000
 This word is to describe someone who is morally aligned with God.

133
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:58,000
 So which is, I think that makes sense to us.

134
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:05,000
 But there is another usage of integrity in the Old Testament, which is tamam.

135
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 So the meaning of this word is to reach an end and to be completed.

136
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:17,000
 This word is frequently used in the books of Leviticus and Numbers,

137
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:28,000
 and with reference to sacrificial animals, which are without blemish and physically whole.

138
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:32,000
 So this is very interesting, right?

139
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:39,000
 Does it ring a bell that Jesus is actually the Lamb of sacrifice?

140
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:43,000
 He sacrificed fully for our sake.

141
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:54,000
 And we as Christians are also called to live as a living sacrifice to Jesus as well.

142
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:01,000
 So today, if we are to ask you to look at your work, to look at how you work,

143
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 would you say it is a whole sacrifice to Jesus?

144
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 I do want to clarify this.

145
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 Working fully for Jesus does not mean that we work 24/7, okay?

146
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:23,000
 But it is to fully align with Jesus' values and His character as we work.

147
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:25,000
 This is what it means.

148
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 So we are to align ourselves with God's values and His character,

149
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:38,000
 no matter how big or how small we feel our work is.

150
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 And throughout these years, working in both corporate and also ministry,

151
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:49,000
 I've seen and I've heard so many Christians really desire to work fully for God,

152
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 and I'm sure many of us here as well.

153
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:57,000
 But it's just so hard to do that, right?

154
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:02,000
 Our work environment is full of brokenness,

155
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:04,000
 it's full of unfairness,

156
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 and it is impossible for us to change a whole environment with our own strength.

157
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:18,000
 And it is so common for us to hear these words in our workplace.

158
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:20,000
 I heard these from Christians as well.

159
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,000
 Let me give you some examples.

160
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:26,000
 I'm not paid enough to do my work.

161
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:30,000
 Or my boss is so mean to us.

162
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:36,000
 Or the company is so unfair in its practices.

163
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:42,000
 So I'll just slack off and not give my 100% to our work.

164
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:47,000
 Or we are seeing everyone in our workplace is doing their bare minimum,

165
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:52,000
 so I'll just do the same to make it fair.

166
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:57,000
 Or we see everyone taking advantage of the reimbursement system,

167
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 so I'll just do the same.

168
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,000
 And perhaps you are thinking,

169
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 "I will give my 100% when I get paid enough,

170
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:10,000
 when I get a better boss,

171
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:16,000
 or when my company is finally fair to me."

172
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:19,000
 But I want to say this to us.

173
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:26,000
 The reality is the world is never going to be perfect.

174
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:33,000
 We will never feel enough, myself included.

175
00:16:33,000 --> 00:16:40,000
 And there's no such perfect human boss or perfect working environment.

176
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:46,000
 With this mindset, we are depending on the environment to shape how we work,

177
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:51,000
 instead of allowing our faith to shape how we work.

178
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:56,000
 When we allow the environment to become our motivation,

179
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 we're still not offering that whole sacrifice to God.

180
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:10,000
 And we have lost our calling to be salt and light in this world.

181
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 As Andrew shared last week,

182
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:16,000
 salt and light is not only just to be different from the world,

183
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,000
 but also to bring changes to the world,

184
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:21,000
 to add flavor to the world,

185
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:24,000
 to preserve the world from decaying,

186
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:29,000
 and to bring light to the darkness.

187
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 But if we are to let the environment to shape how we work,

188
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:36,000
 we become the darkness in the darkness,

189
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:42,000
 and a tasteless salt.

190
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:45,000
 To help us to unpack this idea further,

191
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,000
 I would like to look into a parable

192
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 to see the danger of letting the environment become our motivation at work.

193
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:58,000
 So we will read Luke chapter 16 together.

194
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 Jesus told his disciples,

195
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:05,000
 there was a rich man whose manager was accused of wasting his possessions.

196
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000
 So he called him in and asked him,

197
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:10,000
 "What is this I hear about you?

198
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,000
 Give an account of your management,

199
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:17,000
 because you cannot be manager anymore."

200
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 The manager said to himself,

201
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:20,000
 "What shall I do now?

202
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:23,000
 My master is taking away my job.

203
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:25,000
 I'm not strong enough to dig,

204
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:28,000
 and I'm ashamed to beg.

205
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:33,000
 I know what I'll do so that when I lose my job here,

206
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:36,000
 people will welcome me into their houses."

207
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 So he called in each one of his master's daughters.

208
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:41,000
 He asked the first,

209
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:43,000
 "How much do you owe my master?"

210
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:47,000
 "Three thousand liters of olive oil," he replied.

211
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:48,000
 The manager told him,

212
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 "Take your bill, sit down quickly, and make him fifteen hundred."

213
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:54,000
 Then he asked the second,

214
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:56,000
 "And how much do you owe?"

215
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:00,000
 "Thirty tons of wheat," he replied.

216
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:04,000
 He told him, "Take your bill and make it twenty-four."

217
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:07,000
 The master commended the dishonest manager

218
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:10,000
 because he had added, "Truly,

219
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:13,000
 for the people of this world are more shrewd

220
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:19,000
 in dealing with their own kind than the people of the light."

221
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,000
 So we might feel a little bit confused here right now.

222
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 I get it.

223
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:25,000
 But we will break down this parable

224
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:28,000
 and see what's actually going on in the story.

225
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:31,000
 So the parable starts with a rich man

226
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:34,000
 who heard an accusation about his staff

227
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:37,000
 wasting his money or resources.

228
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:40,000
 And the word "accused" here might be implicating that.

229
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:44,000
 This is a false accusation.

230
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:48,000
 But his immediate response was to lay off his staff.

231
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:50,000
 So the story is pretty messed up

232
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:53,000
 at the beginning of the sentence.

233
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:00,000
 So the manager, without an opportunity to defend himself,

234
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:05,000
 immediately thinks about how he should respond to his situation.

235
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:09,000
 And apparently he still has a notice period in the story,

236
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:13,000
 and he still has the time to be in the office

237
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:17,000
 as a manager for the rich man.

238
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:19,000
 Out of the fear about the future,

239
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 he has decided to take advantage of his position

240
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:28,000
 to lower the debts of his master's debtors

241
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 so that those people owe him a favor

242
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:36,000
 which should possibly benefit him in the future.

243
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:40,000
 So in the Greco-Roman society, there's a culture there.

244
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:42,000
 When someone gives you a favor,

245
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:46,000
 you are almost obliged to give a bigger favor in return.

246
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:49,000
 So this is what the manager was doing.

247
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:53,000
 So I wonder we see the change of effects here.

248
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:57,000
 In the manager's heart, he probably thinks like this.

249
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:00,000
 "My boss is unfair to me.

250
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:04,000
 He trusted all the other people instead of me.

251
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:10,000
 He did not even give me a chance to explain before laying me off.

252
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:17,000
 So I'm going to use my position for my own benefit one last time.

253
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:21,000
 It's not my fault, but his."

254
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:24,000
 It sounds familiar to us, right?

255
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 It sounds like something that we hear in our workplaces.

256
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:33,000
 "Because my boss is unfair, I'm going to make it fair in my own way

257
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:39,000
 by slacking off or by claiming more money than I should, etc, etc."

258
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:42,000
 I want us to see this.

259
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 When we suffer from the darkness of the world,

260
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 it is actually an opportunity for us to choose.

261
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:56,000
 To choose whether we follow the Christ-centered value

262
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:00,000
 to demonstrate the integrity,

263
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:04,000
 or we choose to follow the world's way

264
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:08,000
 to own the value of the world

265
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:13,000
 and extend that suffering and make other people suffer as well.

266
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 So this parable is an example of being darkness in the darkness

267
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:22,000
 and the tasteless salt.

268
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:27,000
 There's one more detail that I would like us to look into,

269
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 which is the action of reducing the debt amount and the master's response.

270
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:35,000
 So there are different debates between the scholars

271
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:38,000
 about how the manager reduced the debt amount.

272
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:42,000
 Some people said that he's actually reducing the high interest

273
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:44,000
 of the debt in those days,

274
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:48,000
 and some people are saying that the manager is eliminating

275
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,000
 the commissions that he should have received,

276
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:54,000
 so he is actually doing a good thing.

277
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:01,000
 But in fact, at the end, the master commended him for acting shrewdly.

278
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:08,000
 What he did might be benefiting for every person in the story.

279
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:11,000
 The debtors actually get to pay less.

280
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 The master may be seen as a generous person

281
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 and he gained his reputation as well.

282
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:21,000
 And the manager is commended by the master.

283
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:25,000
 So it's kind of a win-win-win situation here.

284
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:28,000
 We're not sure about the interest and commission part,

285
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:30,000
 but I want us to see this.

286
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:36,000
 Jesus clearly said that his intention was to find security

287
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:39,000
 after losing his job.

288
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:48,000
 And in 1st Adam, Jesus described the manager as a dishonest manager.

289
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:53,000
 It could be true that he did a good thing for everyone.

290
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:57,000
 It could be true that he's working smartly.

291
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:04,000
 But Jesus also takes his dishonesty into his account.

292
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:11,000
 And Jesus cannot unsee his dishonesty in his heart.

293
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:16,000
 Same to us. Jesus wants the whole of us.

294
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:19,000
 He does not only see the product of our work,

295
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:22,000
 and also he sees our heart.

296
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:25,000
 I wonder how this speaks to us.

297
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:31,000
 It doesn't have to be always dishonesty or false accusation in our workplace.

298
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:34,000
 We can do all the right things in people's eyes.

299
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:39,000
 We can follow all the things that our work requires us to do.

300
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:42,000
 We can have great influence to the people around us,

301
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,000
 and perhaps in the society as well.

302
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:51,000
 But are we demonstrating the values that we believe?

303
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:56,000
 Are we doing the right thing with the right intention,

304
00:24:56,000 --> 00:24:59,000
 even when no one sees it?

305
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:03,000
 And how are we making choices in different situations,

306
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:06,000
 especially in the difficult ones?

307
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:09,000
 Will we choose to uphold our values,

308
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 even if those values are unpopular among our work environment?

309
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:20,000
 So right now I want to share my personal story.

310
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:27,000
 So there was a time that I found my value being very unpopular in my work environment,

311
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:30,000
 and I want to share this with you today.

312
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:33,000
 So I really struggled with my work environment

313
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:37,000
 after I changed from working in a law firm to working in-house.

314
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:40,000
 Not the church.

315
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:43,000
 So the difference between law firm and in-house is,

316
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:46,000
 in a law firm, my original work,

317
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:50,000
 90% of my colleagues are legal professionals.

318
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:56,000
 So we kind of bond by the same professional conduct in our office.

319
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:01,000
 But in-house, which is a commercial company,

320
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:06,000
 where 95% of my colleagues were not legal professionals,

321
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:12,000
 so they are salesperson or they are office support.

322
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:18,000
 So that's when I really struggled with that environment for three reasons.

323
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:19,000
 I will tell you why.

324
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:23,000
 So firstly, I don't know why about one thing.

325
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:26,000
 So until today, I still don't understand that.

326
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:29,000
 So if you understand that, can you tell me after the service

327
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:37,000
 that our staff seem to be very obsessed with knowing the confidential information of the company.

328
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:41,000
 So they will come to me, try to make friends,

329
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:45,000
 and then they will ask me to tell them something confidential,

330
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 perhaps the HR movement,

331
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:55,000
 or some confidential or personal data of a certain staff member.

332
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:58,000
 But to me, as a legal professional,

333
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:01,000
 my biggest commitment is confidentiality.

334
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:04,000
 I can't tell you this.

335
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:10,000
 So I was quite frustrated with these interactions in the first place.

336
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:14,000
 And the other thing that I struggle with is,

337
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:19,000
 the staff will constantly tell me that certain things I'm supposed to do.

338
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:23,000
 But to me, those clearly are not within the legal scope.

339
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:25,000
 So I didn't quite understand why.

340
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:30,000
 But I feel like I'm a person with good boundaries.

341
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:31,000
 So I'm okay with saying no.

342
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:34,000
 So I would just say, "Oh, I don't think so."

343
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:39,000
 But here is the thing that I most struggle with.

344
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:41,000
 So whenever I say no to people,

345
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:45,000
 whenever it's about the confidential data,

346
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:49,000
 or whether it is about doing certain things that I'm not supposed to do,

347
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 they will say something like this to me.

348
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:52,000
 And I'm not kidding.

349
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:55,000
 Throughout my time there, for more than two years,

350
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:59,000
 people are still saying that to me before I left the company.

351
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:01,000
 They say something like this.

352
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:07,000
 "Listen, the former staff in your position would do that."

353
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:10,000
 And this is not the most hurting part.

354
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:12,000
 Here it is.

355
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:17,000
 "She is popular among the staff, and you are not."

356
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:23,000
 And I'm like, "Ouch! What have I done to you?"

357
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,000
 And I really struggle at some points,

358
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:29,000
 because the environment was nothing like that in law firm,

359
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 that I had good relationships with my colleagues.

360
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:33,000
 So I don't know why.

361
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:36,000
 I don't understand why people would say this to me.

362
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:39,000
 And so I really struggled, and I prayed.

363
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 I prayed for my work environment.

364
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:45,000
 I prayed that God would speak to me, and he did,

365
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:49,000
 which is the dangerous part.

366
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:51,000
 So one day I was praying,

367
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,000
 and he reminded me of a conversation with him

368
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:59,000
 at the very beginning of my training in law school.

369
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:02,000
 So I remember one night, God was saying to me,

370
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:07,000
 "Jennifer, I want you to be different."

371
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:09,000
 Not in the sense that you need to be different,

372
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:12,000
 rebelliously different from everyone else,

373
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:16,000
 but being able to discern what is right,

374
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:21,000
 even if everyone else is telling you the opposite.

375
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:24,000
 So I was reminded of that,

376
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:27,000
 and so I had to make a choice,

377
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:30,000
 whether I listen to those voices,

378
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:33,000
 or I listen to Jesus.

379
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:36,000
 And I couldn't bear the result of not listening to Jesus

380
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:39,000
 when he actually speaks to you.

381
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:44,000
 So I just try to continue, to try to uphold my value,

382
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:49,000
 try to trust that God is doing his work behind the scenes.

383
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:52,000
 And he is gracious enough to show me

384
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:54,000
 that I'm actually making an impact.

385
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:55,000
 It's not a big impact,

386
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:57,000
 I did not change the whole work environment,

387
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:59,000
 but I remember one day,

388
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:03,000
 it was very close to the end of my time there.

389
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:06,000
 I worked there for two years already,

390
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,000
 and then one colleague came up to me.

391
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:11,000
 We didn't really talk in the past,

392
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:13,000
 throughout the two years.

393
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:15,000
 We're from different department.

394
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
 So she came to me and she said,

395
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:25,000
 "Jennifer, I see that you're having a different approach at your work."

396
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:29,000
 First of all, that you really value

397
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:31,000
 teaching people to do their work

398
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:34,000
 instead of doing the work for other people,

399
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:37,000
 which I think our company needs that,

400
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:39,000
 and I appreciate that.

401
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:42,000
 And also, the other thing is,

402
00:30:42,000 --> 00:30:46,000
 I see that you're not a fan of pleasing people,

403
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:48,000
 and you don't compromise,

404
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:52,000
 no matter how people commented about your work.

405
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:55,000
 And that motivates me, my colleague,

406
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:00,000
 to hold on to her values in her role as well.

407
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:04,000
 So it's kind of encouraging to me personally,

408
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:07,000
 on all the things that I've been trying to do.

409
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:10,000
 I don't know how my story speaks to you.

410
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:13,000
 You might be expecting a testimony with a bigger impact

411
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,000
 or more immediate impact,

412
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:18,000
 but that's my two years story.

413
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:20,000
 But I want to say that,

414
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:24,000
 no matter which area, which industry you're working in,

415
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:26,000
 we are living in a tension

416
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:29,000
 between the values of the world

417
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:31,000
 and the values of Christ.

418
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:36,000
 And the world is going to tell you every single day

419
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:39,000
 how you should be working

420
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:43,000
 and what value you should be upholding.

421
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:46,000
 And you will need to make a choice.

422
00:31:46,000 --> 00:31:50,000
 You will need to choose whether you follow those voices

423
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:56,000
 or you follow the voice from God.

424
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:59,000
 Yeah, so you could be working in a different industry.

425
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:00,000
 Let me give you some examples.

426
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:02,000
 If you work in academia,

427
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:05,000
 you might be told that you need to publish more papers,

428
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:08,000
 you need to earn the academic reputation.

429
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:10,000
 If you are a salesperson,

430
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:13,000
 you will be told that you need to hit the target,

431
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:17,000
 you need to earn the most money from the person in front of you

432
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:20,000
 or from the company that you're working with,

433
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:24,000
 or you're working in an office with some routine work

434
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:25,000
 and people will tell you,

435
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:30,000
 "Don't ask questions, just follow what everyone else do."

436
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:35,000
 But I want us to ask this question,

437
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:38,000
 "What does Jesus say about that?"

438
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:44,000
 "What does Jesus say on the things that people are telling you?"

439
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:46,000
 I don't think I can give a straightforward answer

440
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:51,000
 or I can't give you a formula that you follow A, B, and C,

441
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:56,000
 then we are flourishing for Jesus in our workplace.

442
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:02,000
 It is really a conversation between you and Jesus personally.

443
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:05,000
 It takes a long-term effort.

444
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:10,000
 It's not like we do something nice and we check it off the box.

445
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:14,000
 Demonstrating our values requires our commitment and persistence.

446
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:19,000
 Firstly, we need to commit to constantly seek

447
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:22,000
 what is fitting in Jesus' eyes.

448
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:28,000
 And then we need to persist in following that as we work.

449
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:33,000
 When it comes to be sought and liked,

450
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:35,000
 it takes consistent effort.

451
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:40,000
 We need to persist our faith and our value in long-term basis.

452
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:46,000
 And we can expect we will face some challenges and temptations along the way.

453
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:49,000
 We will need to challenge the mindset of

454
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:54,000
 "Everyone else is doing the same, so I'll just do the same."

455
00:33:54,000 --> 00:34:01,000
 You may be thinking, "What if I suffer even more if I work differently?"

456
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:06,000
 Or you might be thinking, "What if my boss and my colleagues

457
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:09,000
 take advantage of me if I work differently?"

458
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:11,000
 It could happen, right?

459
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:14,000
 But I want to say this to us.

460
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:19,000
 To follow Jesus is also to extend the grace

461
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:23,000
 and the light that we have received from Jesus.

462
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:30,000
 And the grace that we have received has already changed our whole life.

463
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:35,000
 And it is our turn to be sought and liked,

464
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:38,000
 to be different from the world,

465
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:45,000
 to change the state of blindness and darkness around us.

466
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:51,000
 And this is the purpose when we are doing our actual work.

467
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:56,000
 We are demonstrating the light, the hope,

468
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:59,000
 and the grace to the people around us,

469
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:02,000
 although we don't always see it.

470
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:09,000
 And we will need to hold on to Jesus by faith to be able to do that.

471
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:16,000
 So I've been talking a lot, and in this sermon series,

472
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:22,000
 we believe that it will be helpful for us to hear different voices from our community.

473
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:26,000
 So I've shared my story, and we will hear another story

474
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:29,000
 from one of our congregation members from our community,

475
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:33,000
 who is Chris Webster. He works in a totally different industry,

476
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:37,000
 and he's going to come up and share his testimony with us.

477
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:40,000
 So would you join me to welcome Chris to the stage?

478
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:51,000
 Thank you, Jennifer.

479
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:54,000
 My voice is getting stronger over the day.

480
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:58,000
 It starts off pretty weak. Excuse me a minute.

481
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:02,000
 That was amazing, Jennifer.

482
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:09,000
 Being different, being accused, being attacked, being misunderstood.

483
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:12,000
 Jesus has been there before, right?

484
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:19,000
 I want to share a life hack, a spiritual life hack that I was given

485
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:22,000
 roughly when I was about this age of the congregation.

486
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:29,000
 But first of all, to Moses, one of my heroes.

487
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:33,000
 Somewhat over 3,000 years ago,

488
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 Moses was moving into his second big career change.

489
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:43,000
 This one was going to be leading a nation, nation building.

490
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:45,000
 Never done it before.

491
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:49,000
 And he spent those epic 40 nights on the mountain,

492
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:53,000
 the mountain that Andrews visited in person.

493
00:36:53,000 --> 00:37:01,000
 And getting a download from God about what this job is going to entail.

494
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:04,000
 He was briefed by God himself. Great tip.

495
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:10,000
 Everything came. Social relationships, economic relationships,

496
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:15,000
 how to handle animal husbandry, matters of life and death,

497
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:22,000
 the structure of the executive, the structure of the judiciary, everything.

498
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:31,000
 Religion. At the end of the chapters in Exodus that narrate this,

499
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:35,000
 there's a hiatus, a pause, a summary.

500
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:40,000
 What will God choose to emphasize?

501
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:44,000
 Will it be the first commandment, the first great commandment?

502
00:37:44,000 --> 00:37:51,000
 Or will it be the sacrificial bits of the religion that portend Jesus's own sacrifice?

503
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:56,000
 1,300 years later. It was the Sabbath.

504
00:37:56,000 --> 00:38:03,000
 The fourth of the commandments. What's that about?

505
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:13,000
 When I was doing my A-levels, not quite so long ago as Moses, but almost,

506
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:18,000
 in London, Jesus came and whispered to me,

507
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:28,000
 "Will you adopt a spiritual principle discipline that will guide your career and your life?"

508
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:35,000
 Not just the A-levels that you're about to face. Excuse me.

509
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:40,000
 He said, "It's the spirit of the Sabbath." Not the law of the Sabbath.

510
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:44,000
 Not bound by that. That was the Hebrews. The spirit of the Sabbath.

511
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:47,000
 The principle of the Sabbath. What's the spirit of the Sabbath?

512
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:56,000
 Well, what came to me, and one interpretation of that aspect of the Sabbath is,

513
00:38:56,000 --> 00:39:00,000
 we all have seven days in which to labor.

514
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:08,000
 To the Hebrews, in principle, you have seven days to plow the fields, to plant, to water,

515
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:12,000
 to put the manure on it, to harvest, to make the hay.

516
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:18,000
 I've worked on a farm, and I know that you do not stop on a Sunday.

517
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:22,000
 You have to get everything in, otherwise you can lose some of it.

518
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:30,000
 To the Hebrews, you will be at a disadvantage if you follow my rule on the Sabbath.

519
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:34,000
 To students, to me when I was your age, some of you,

520
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:42,000
 other students around you will be studying 24/7, plus plus in Hong Kong.

521
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:47,000
 You will be at a disadvantage to me. I'm not asking you to do this.

522
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:59,000
 I'm not expecting parents to write to Andrew or, you know, measure this, measure it.

523
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:05,000
 Pause. Download from heaven. Hear what God wants.

524
00:40:05,000 --> 00:40:09,000
 And I will be with you, and I will make it up.

525
00:40:09,000 --> 00:40:17,000
 It's the Sabbath in that sense is, it's an implementation of the idea of meekness.

526
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:22,000
 Meekness, Andrew taught us some months ago, I think, is having the power to do something,

527
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:24,000
 but choosing not to use it.

528
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:29,000
 You're the greatest debater, and you're arguing with somebody who's not.

529
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:33,000
 Desist. Stand back. Let them win.

530
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:39,000
 You're a powerful boss. You could easily wipe the floor with some of your competitors.

531
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:44,000
 Don't. Stand back. Let them have the floor.

532
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:47,000
 Meekness, one of the greatest virtues.

533
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:52,000
 Jesus himself embodied meekness in such a powerful way.

534
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:56,000
 He left everything behind. His mightiness.

535
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:00,000
 We often think about Jesus as somebody who knew everything,

536
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:03,000
 could remember right back to phase one of creation.

537
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:07,000
 I don't think he could. Did he as a baby? Probably not.

538
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:11,000
 At which point then did he learn it? I think he learned it from his heavenly father.

539
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:15,000
 He put it all aside. Meekness.

540
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:18,000
 So, sabbathing, meekness.

541
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:25,000
 So I did. I accepted the challenge when I was, how old were you with the A-levels? 18? 19?

542
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:29,000
 Come the exams, up to the precipice.

543
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:32,000
 Shall I work on a Sunday? No.

544
00:41:32,000 --> 00:41:35,000
 I'm going to finish my revision on a Saturday.

545
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:38,000
 Again, no words from parents here, please.

546
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:43,000
 You have to do what God is asking you to do yourself.

547
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:46,000
 Undergraduate degree, same. Postgraduate degree, same.

548
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:53,000
 Work right through my career. I'm a professor at Hong Kong U.

549
00:41:53,000 --> 00:42:00,000
 When my students or young academic mentees come and ask,

550
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:04,000
 how do you become a successful professor in Hong Kong U?

551
00:42:04,000 --> 00:42:10,000
 For those, often I just give the sort of advice they want to hear.

552
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:14,000
 Or rather, the advice they need.

553
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:21,000
 But for those who have ears to hear, I'll tell them meekness stories.

554
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:28,000
 I'll tell them faith stories. Like on my most difficult days when I was dean,

555
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:33,000
 I was dean for 11 years at Hong Kong U, managing one of its 10 faculties.

556
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:40,000
 For the most difficult days, I would get up, get going an extra hour,

557
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:45,000
 an extra two hours early to pray, to meditate,

558
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:51,000
 to make sure that before I stepped foot into my workplace,

559
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:53,000
 I carried Jesus with me.

560
00:42:53,000 --> 00:43:00,000
 And I knew that could save hours and hours and hours, days, weeks, litigation, everything.

561
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:04,000
 But if you go in with the spirit of Jesus, he can solve it in a minute.

562
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:07,000
 Not always, but he can.

563
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:14,000
 So finally, how does that personal story, a personal discipline,

564
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:22,000
 impact the workplace and all that Jennifer's told us about the challenges therein?

565
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:28,000
 Well, it changes you and you change the workplace.

566
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:37,000
 I love the bit in Revelation 19 that says,

567
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:41,000
 "The spirit of prophecy is the testimony of Jesus."

568
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:45,000
 It fits very nicely the other way around, slightly different meaning.

569
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:49,000
 The testimony of Jesus is the spirit of prophecy.

570
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:57,000
 When you Sabbath, or when you fast, or when you pray, you're giving up something.

571
00:43:57,000 --> 00:43:59,000
 You're saying, "I can't do it on my own.

572
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:02,000
 I'm going to go into work with one hand tied behind my back

573
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:07,000
 because I want you to do it, not me to do it."

574
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:13,000
 And when you do that, the Father, the Son, and Holy Spirit embrace you

575
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:15,000
 and fill you with the spirit.

576
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:22,000
 And they say to your Sabbathing, like they do to your secret fasting,

577
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:29,000
 when you do it in secret, your Father in heaven will see what you do in secret

578
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:32,000
 and will reward you.

579
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:34,000
 And how does he reward you?

580
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:40,000
 He rewards you by giving you more of the spirit of prophecy.

581
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:44,000
 So you become more of a testimony of Jesus.

582
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:49,000
 But how did we ever think that we did things to change the workplace,

583
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:55,000
 that we had to learn ABCD of workplace evangelism?

584
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:57,000
 There's a place for that.

585
00:44:57,000 --> 00:44:59,000
 Jesus does it.

586
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:03,000
 He fills you, and he impacts, and he changes you.

587
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:08,000
 I was thinking of Jennifer's problem.

588
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:09,000
 You never know.

589
00:45:09,000 --> 00:45:14,000
 That lady you talked about, it might have been that the only reason why you're employed

590
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:18,000
 for two years was to give her that lesson.

591
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:20,000
 You don't know what she went on to do.

592
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:21,000
 That's how God works.

593
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:25,000
 One person like a lost sheep from the spirit of Christ working in you.

594
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:27,000
 Thank you.

595
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:31,000
 [applause]

596
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:33,000
 Thank you so much, Chris.

597
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:36,000
 Hopefully, Chris, this story will encourage you as well,

598
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:43,000
 that when we choose to uphold God's value in the workplace,

599
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:49,000
 and Jesus is there, the Holy Spirit will help us to get through that.

600
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:54,000
 So it will look differently to your own stories, to your own work that you are doing.

601
00:45:54,000 --> 00:45:56,000
 We believe that.

602
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:02,000
 After all, we are asking Jesus, "What do you say about my work?"

603
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:08,000
 So I encourage you, after today, that you will start having that conversation with Jesus,

604
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:14,000
 between you and Jesus, to ask Him, "What do you say about my work?

605
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:20,000
 How do you want me to uphold your values in our work?"

606
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:27,000
 So right now, I want to invite us to stand and we pray together.

607
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:30,000
 I would like to pray for you.

608
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:39,000
 First of all, I want to recognize that some of us in this room, you might really struggle with your work.

609
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:46,000
 You really struggle with maybe the craziness of the hours or the intensity of your work.

610
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:48,000
 You might be struggling with the environment.

611
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:51,000
 We will pray for you if that's you.

612
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:56,000
 And then we will pray that Jesus will speak to you.

613
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:00,000
 You might think, "I've never heard Jesus speaking to me in this area."

614
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:06,000
 But Jesus promised us that when we ask, He will answer.

615
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:11,000
 So we will take a moment to ask Him to speak to each of us.

616
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:20,000
 And lastly, we will pray that the power of the Spirit will give you the strength to actually persist,

617
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:23,000
 to follow Him in the workplace.

618
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:28,000
 So would you join me in prayer?

619
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:30,000
 Jesus, we thank you.

620
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:36,000
 We thank you that you sacrificed for us.

621
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:41,000
 And thank you for your goodness for each human being in this world.

622
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:47,000
 And you intend all of us to live under your grace.

623
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:54,000
 And Lord, we thank you that you called us to be part of your work,

624
00:47:54,000 --> 00:48:02,000
 to be part of the light that shines into the darkness in the world.

625
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:08,000
 And we want to come before you to recognize our limitations,

626
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:15,000
 to bring our weakness, to bring our struggles in front of you.

627
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:25,000
 And we pray for those among our brothers and sisters who are really struggling to see you in the workplace.

628
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:27,000
 Jesus, would you come?

629
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:34,000
 Would you come and give us the grace that is enough for us each day?

630
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:39,000
 Give us the courage, the strength to overcome the challenges,

631
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:46,000
 to overcome the struggles that we face each day.

632
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:54,000
 And Jesus, we also want to pray for each of us as you have called each of us to be your salt and light.

633
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:01,000
 Lord, we invite you to speak to us in terms of our work.

634
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:04,000
 There are so many voices that we hear each day.

635
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:07,000
 Everyone is telling us how we are supposed to work.

636
00:49:07,000 --> 00:49:10,000
 But Lord, we want to hear your voice.

637
00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:15,000
 Lord, speak to us.

638
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:20,000
 Speak to us on how we are supposed to work for you.

639
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:28,000
 Speak to us on how we are working with you in all the things that we are doing daily,

640
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:32,000
 no matter how big, how small it looks like.

641
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:40,000
 Jesus, we pray that your voice will be louder than all the other voices that we hear each day.

642
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:42,000
 And we will hold on to that.

643
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:46,000
 We desire to live fully for you.

644
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:49,000
 We desire to work for you.

645
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:54,000
 So Jesus, would you help us?

646
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:03,000
 And Lord, we want to ask for your Spirit, because we can't do this without our own strength.

647
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:12,000
 Holy Spirit, we ask that you will give us the strength, the wisdom,

648
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:16,000
 and the persistence that we need in our workplace.

649
00:50:16,000 --> 00:50:24,000
 We persist to uphold your values, to uphold you in all the things that we are doing.

650
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:29,000
 So Lord, we ask for your help in our workplace.

651
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:34,000
 And we thank you that we get to worship with our brothers and sisters together.

652
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:40,000
 We thank you that you speak to us, you speak to the areas that perhaps we struggle the most.

653
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:47,000
 And we pray that tomorrow when we wake up, that we still see you, we are still connected with you,

654
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:49,000
 even though we are struggling in our workplace.

655
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:54,000
 So Lord, will you be with us as we work?

656
00:50:54,000 --> 00:50:58,000
 And we thank you, in Jesus' name. Amen.

657
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:00,580
 (gentle music)

